Workshop organized by Keith & Jess

From The Ground Up:

From the ground up represents footwork as a foundation. Also a metaphor for being rooted into the earth. Knowing that anytime you need to begin again your start by planting the seed of footwork.

Footwork:
We will offer Popping footwork foundation/traditions and ways to create new patterns through application.

Floorwork:
It‚Äôs easy to think of the floor as just blow ups. We will share how to play with rhythms on the floor to help you make your floor game feel like your dancing on your feet. We will offer foundation/traditional shoot downs and variations.

Presentation:
How fashion, style and character play an important role in the dance. Understanding and breaking down how it can influence, highlight movement and different parts of the body.

Are you curious about the venue? Say no more,
This is a time lapse of our venue/info & how to get there.

The venue includes:
- Bathrooms
- Water fountain (in the community center next door)
- wheelchair lift for accessibility 
- Seating
- brand new stage for dancers
- greenroom for competitors & judges
- FREE Parking on site (first come, first serve) 

Subway transit:

The venue is located about 10 minutes driving from Shephard yonge station and 15 minutes from Sheppard west station (30 min walk). You can also take the 84D from Sheppard- Yonge station 7 stops to Bathurst St, which is 9 mins walking from Earl Bales Park 
Or take the 984 from Sheppard West station Bathurst Street, which is an 8 min walk from Earl Bales Park.

*Sunscreen, bug spray, and water will be provided for all contestants.*
(But bring your own just in case)
* Bring umbrella (prepare for weather bit gets very sunny)
* Bring a refillable water bottle. The community center next door has a water fountain *

We will provide food to contestants in the green room backstage but bring your own as well. It's going to be a long day dancing outdoors, please come prepared.

Open Jam Collective is a street dance group in Toronto that aims to keep the legacy of street dance culture alive by creating spaces and opportunities for exchange, knowledge-sharing and growth. 

On Friday, June 16, our group members alongside prominent street dancers in Toronto, including @raoulwilke @tommysteeze1973 @carolineladyc brought street dance and street dance culture to high school youth at Weston Collegiate Institute (WCI). 

It was a great experience connecting Weston Alumni street dancers to current WCI students, and showcasing Black-created street dance that is currently thriving in the city! We look forward to continuing to engage with these youth at future events!

Thank you to @equitas_human_rights for financially supporting us, and providing us with an opportunity to build within the community!

üì∏:@panda.danz

Wow, look at our baby go! What started off as a small groupchat for a trip to MTL, has now become the community we dreamt it to be. We started "Oatmilk&Jam" as a way to facilitate sessions post pandemic during a time when many venues were closed, sessions were few and far apart, and events were scarce. As our family grew, we decided that the community deserved more events, and we were in a position to deliver them for FREE! 

Now here we are 4 events, dozens of street performances, and countless sessions later, still as hungry as ever. The phrase "by the community, for the community"
has never been more true than it is right now.
But as things grow, we as a collective must also grow and embrace change. 

Thus, we have decided to relaunch and rebrand. Introducing:
 "Open Jam Collective" aka "OJC". 
Thank you to everyone who has contributed and played a part in getting us here, we are so grateful for your support. With that being said, keep an eye out for what's next because this is just the beginning ;)
